  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(6) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Over the household,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—like the “High Steward” of a modern Court. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 18:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " we have the same three officers mentioned (“Eliakim, who was over the household, and Shebna the scribe, and Joah the son of Asaph the recorder”).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Adoniram . . . over the tribute (or “levy”),—evidently the head of Solomon’s great public works. (See 1Kings 5:14.) The name is elsewhere given as Adoram. It is to be noticed that in the enumeration of David’s officers in the early part of the reign (2Samuel 8:16-18) no such officer is found; but that in the latter part of his reign the list contains the name of Adoram (2Samuel 20:24). It has been thought that the numbering of the people recorded in 2 Samuel 24 and 1 Chronicles 21, was in preparation for such forced work, and hence was odious to Joab and others. In 1Kings 12:18 we read how the holder of this office, being naturally most unpopular with those who had felt the burden of Solomon’s splendour, was stoned to death in the insurrection against Rehoboam.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Adoniram . . . over the tribute ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(or “levy”),—evidently the head of Solomon’s great public works. (See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Kings 5:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) The name is elsewhere given as ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Adoram. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "It is to be noticed that in the enumeration of David’s officers in the early part of the reign (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 8:16-18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ")",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": " no ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "such officer is found; but that in the latter part of his reign the list contains the name of Adoram (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 20:24",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). It has been thought that the numbering of the people recorded in 2 Samuel 24 and 1 Chronicles 21, was in preparation for such forced work, and hence was odious to Joab and others. In ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Kings 12:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " we read how the holder of this office, being naturally most unpopular with those who had felt the burden of Solomon’s splendour, was stoned to death in the insurrection against Rehoboam.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To this list the Greek Version adds: “Eliab the son of Shaphat was over the body-guard.” As the office of captain of the body-guard is found in the other lists, and is too important to be omitted, it is possible that this addition corrects some defect in the Hebrew text. Yet it is also possible that no successor to Benaiah was appointed, as experience had shown, in the crushing of the rebellion of Adonijah, how easily the captaincy of the body-guard might become a quasi-independent power.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
